  "slug": "svickova-na-smetane",
  "title": "Svíčková na Smetaně",
  "subtitle": "Czech braised beef sirloin with cream sauce",
  "excerpt": "Beef sirloin slowly braised on a bed of root vegetables, then sliced and served under a silky, sweet-sour cream sauce with a slice of bread dumpling and a spoon of cranberry. The Czech national dish.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Svíčková na smetaně is Czechia's most iconic dish, served on Sundays and at celebrations. Documented in Lesley Chamberlain, The Food and Cooking of Eastern Europe (1989) and Josephine Bacon, The Complete Book of Czech and Slovak Cooking (1999). The sweet-sour cream sauce (made from the braising vegetables) is unique to Czech cooking.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Svíčková na smetaně is not a dish you make quickly. The beef needs 2 to 2.5 hours in the oven; the sauce needs patience and the right balance of sweet and sour to be correct. But the result is tender sliced beef under a pale, velvety cream sauce that is simultaneously sweet, sharp, and deeply savoury, unlike anything else.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The sauce is made by blending the braising vegetables (carrot, parsnip, celeriac, onion) with the cooking liquid and cream. Its character comes from lemon juice or vinegar to sharpen it, sugar to balance, and a good amount of cream poured in at the end. Cranberry jam (brusinky) is the traditional accompaniment, spooned on top of the sauce at the table.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
