      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Sear and braise",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 160°C fan. Melt the butter in a large casserole over high heat and sear the beef joint on all sides until deep brown, about 8 minutes. Transfer to a plate. Add all the vegetables, lemon juice and zest, bay, allspice, peppercorns, and thyme to the casserole. Stir for 2 minutes. Nestle the beef on top. Add the wine and stock, the liquid should come about halfway up the joint. Cover tightly and braise for 2 to 2.5 hours until very tender.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the cream sauce",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Remove the beef and rest it. Strain the braising liquid and reserve. Put the cooked vegetables into a blender with enough braising liquid to blend smoothly. Pour into a saucepan and add the cream, vinegar, sugar, and salt. Simmer for 5 minutes, stirring. Adjust the sweet-sour balance: it should be noticeably sweet-sharp, not neutral. Slice the beef and reheat briefly in the sauce or return it to the pot and ladle the sauce over.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Simmer uncovered to reduce; or add a tablespoon of plain flour stirred into a little cold cream before adding to the pan",
              "cause": "Vegetables not blended finely enough, or too much braising liquid added",
              "symptom": "Sauce is too thin"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add both in small increments and taste; the sweet and sour should be in balance, both present and neither dominant",
              "cause": "Under-seasoned with vinegar and sugar",
              "symptom": "Sauce tastes flat, missing the sweet-sour balance"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Svíčková na smetaně is Sunday lunch in Czechia. It arrives with two slices of bread dumpling (houskový knedlík) placed beside the beef and a generous spoon of cranberry compote (brusinky) on top of the sauce, the cranberry is not garnish but part of the flavour. Czechs have strong opinions about the correct sweet-sour ratio in the sauce, and every family has its own calibrated version.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
